rt–Medicine Collaborative Practice will resonate with people with head or neck cancer as well as medical practitioners who aid in their healing process. It is an important book for all those in the health professions and medical humanities, as well as artists, arts-based researchers, and those interested in the areas of health and visual communication and knowledge translation. Contributors: Ingrid Bachmann, Pamela Brett-MacLean, Sean Caulfield, Kimberly Flowers, Jude Griebel, Bahaa Harmouche, Jill Ho-You, Heather Huston, Bernie Krewski, Lianne McTavish, Suresh Nayar, Bradley Necyk, Leslie O’Connor-Parsons, Kyle Terrence, Helen Vallianatos, Minn N. Yoon  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCancer in art. 0aCancerxPatients. 0aCancerxTreatment. 0aHeadxCancerxPatients. 0aMedicine and art. 0aNeckxCancerxPatients. 0aVisual communication. 7aART / Canadian.2bisacsh  aMedicine in the Arts / Cancer Patients / Visual Communication.1 aBachmann, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrett-MacLean, Pamela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrett-Maclean, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaulfield, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlowers, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriebel, Jude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarmouche, Bahaa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHo-You, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuston, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrewski, Bernie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcTavish, Lianne, eeditor.4edt4http